---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Pest Control Services | A2Z Pest Control LLC" description="Complete pest control services for Pittsburgh homes. Ants, rodents, roaches, stinging insects, centipedes, fleas, moths, silverfish, earwigs, and more.">

  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1 class="page-title">Our Services</h1>
      <p class="page-intro">A2Z Pest Control handles residential pest problems across Allegheny, Butler, and Washington Counties. Here's what we treat, how to identify each pest, and what to expect.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ANTS -->
  <section class="pest-detail section" id="ants">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="detail-layout">
        <div class="detail-specimen">
          <div class="specimen-panel">
            <img src="/images/shutterstock_73929577_-_version_2.jpg" alt="Carpenter ant close-up" width="3420" height="1922" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
          <div class="specimen-panel specimen-panel-sm">
            <img src="/images/shutterstock_212656306.jpg" alt="Odorous house ant" width="1000" height="667" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="detail-text reveal">
          <span class="detail-tag">Most Common</span>
          <h2>Ants</h2>
          <div class="pest-types">
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Carpenter Ant</h3>
              <p>Among the largest ants, from one-fourth to three-eighths inch long. Most common species is black, but some have reddish or yellowish coloring. Workers have large mandibles.</p>
              <p>They normally nest in dead portions of standing trees, stumps or logs, but invade homes in search of food. Nests inside homes can do significant damage. They hollow out "galleries" in wood that are so smooth they appear sandpapered.</p>
              <p>All kinds of houses, regardless of age or type of construction, are vulnerable to infestation. Colonies can contain up to 3,000 workers. Swarms of winged reproductives emerging inside a home in spring are a sure sign of an interior colony.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Odorous House Ant</h3>
              <p>Dark reddish brown to black, one-tenth inch long. Most likely to invade homes during rainy weather. They travel in trails and forage day and night. When crushed, give off a very unpleasant odor. Colonies are very large.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Pavement Ant</h3>
              <p>Light brown to black, about one-tenth inch long. Invade homes foraging for food throughout the year. Nests are outdoors under stones, along curbing, or in cracks of pavement. They can nest indoors in walls and under floors. A particular nuisance around homes with slab-on-grade construction.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- RODENTS -->
  <section class="pest-detail pest-detail-alt section" id="rodents">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="detail-layout detail-layout-reverse">
        <div class="detail-specimen">
          <div class="specimen-panel">
            <img src="/images/11226_1429114652_137_11226.jpg" alt="House mouse" width="599" height="364" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
          <div class="specimen-panel specimen-panel-sm">
            <img src="/images/13687_1427306499_54_13687.jpg" alt="Rat" width="599" height="599" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="detail-text reveal">
          <span class="detail-tag">Health Risk</span>
          <h2>Rodents</h2>
          <div class="pest-types">
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>House Mouse</h3>
              <p>Small and slender, three to four inches long, with large ears, small eyes, and pointed nose. Light brown or light gray with rod-shaped droppings.</p>
              <p>They nest within structures and burrow, establishing a "territory" near food sources, generally 10 to 30 feet from the nest. Excellent climbers. Prolific breeders at two months, with litters as often as every 40 to 50 days.</p>
              <p>They feed 15 to 20 times per day, can squeeze through a hole one-fourth inch wide, and carry many serious diseases.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Rats</h3>
              <p>Larger than mice, rats are destructive and dangerous. They contaminate food, cause structural damage by gnawing, and carry diseases. Professional treatment is critical as rats are wary of new objects in their environment, making DIY approaches unreliable.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ROACHES & BOXELDER -->
  <section class="pest-detail section" id="roaches">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="detail-layout">
        <div class="detail-specimen">
          <div class="specimen-panel">
            <img src="/images/13661_1427306498_19_13661.jpg" alt="Cockroach" width="599" height="599" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="detail-text reveal">
          <span class="detail-tag">Persistent</span>
          <h2 id="boxelder">Roaches &amp; Boxelder Bugs</h2>
          <div class="pest-types">
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Cockroaches</h3>
              <p>Cockroaches are among the most resilient household pests. They contaminate food, leave allergens in their droppings, and reproduce rapidly. Professional treatment targets both visible roaches and hidden colonies behind walls and under appliances.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Boxelder Bugs</h3>
              <p>About half an inch long, black with orange or red markings. Generally not noticed during summer, but often become an issue when they try to move into homes during fall as they search for overwintering sites.</p>
              <p>Primarily a nuisance because they enter homes in large numbers. When abundant, they can stain walls, curtains, and other surfaces with their excrement.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- STINGING INSECTS -->
  <section class="pest-detail pest-detail-alt section" id="stinging">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="detail-layout detail-layout-reverse">
        <div class="detail-specimen">
          <div class="specimen-panel">
            <img src="/images/shutterstock_161299019.jpg" alt="Carpenter bee" width="1000" height="979" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="detail-text reveal">
          <span class="detail-tag detail-tag-warn">Exterior Only</span>
          <h2>Stinging Insects</h2>
          <div class="pest-types">
            <div class="pest-type">
              <p>Wasps, yellow jackets, bumble bees, hornets, carpenter bees, and other dangerous stinging insects. We treat them on the exterior of your house.</p>
              <p>Many homemade treatments do not work, and you could get stung in the process.</p>
              <p class="pest-warning"><strong>Do not seal any holes until the nest is professionally treated.</strong> Sealing entry points before treatment traps insects inside walls, causing them to find alternate routes into your living space.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CENTIPEDES & MILLIPEDES -->
  <section class="pest-detail section" id="centipedes">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="detail-layout">
        <div class="detail-specimen">
          <div class="specimen-panel">
            <img src="/images/shutterstock_133014917.jpg" alt="House centipede" width="1000" height="667" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
          <div class="specimen-panel specimen-panel-sm">
            <img src="/images/shutterstock_194141441.jpg" alt="Millipede" width="1000" height="667" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="detail-text reveal">
          <span class="detail-tag">Moisture Pest</span>
          <h2>Centipedes &amp; Millipedes</h2>
          <div class="pest-types">
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Centipedes</h3>
              <p>The house centipede runs rapidly, holding its body well elevated, suddenly stops, then runs again. One to two inches long, with very long slender antennae and 15 pairs of long legs. Grayish yellow to brown with 3 longitudinal dorsal stripes.</p>
              <p>Found in wet, damp places, especially basements, in overwatered potted plants, and in bathrooms. Their bite can be painful but is not generally toxic to humans.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Millipedes</h3>
              <p>Brownish and worm-like with many body segments and two pairs of legs on each segment. They typically live outside in moist vegetation, leaf litter, and mulch. When conditions are right, migrations can occur and large numbers will find their way inside through cracks and crevices.</p>
              <p>Infestations can build up quickly. A combination of moisture control and treatment provides the best results.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FLEAS -->
  <section class="pest-detail pest-detail-alt section" id="fleas">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="detail-layout detail-layout-reverse">
        <div class="detail-specimen">
          <div class="specimen-panel">
            <img src="/images/shutterstock_71639218.jpg" alt="Flea close-up" width="1000" height="667" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="detail-text reveal">
          <span class="detail-tag">Pet Owners</span>
          <h2>Fleas</h2>
          <div class="pest-types">
            <div class="pest-type">
              <p>Very small, wingless, 1/12 to 1/6 inch long. Their narrow bodies allow movement in tight areas, and backward-projecting spines make them difficult to remove by shaking or scratching.</p>
              <p>Adults feed on blood. A female will lay up to 200 to 400 eggs. Eggs are deposited on hosts or on floors, upholstery, and pet bedding. Flea larvae are active and hard to spot, found deep in carpets or cracks and crevices of floors.</p>
              <p>Fleas go through four distinct stages: eggs, larvae, pupae, and adult. Complete treatment needs to address every stage of the lifecycle.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MOTHS -->
  <section class="pest-detail section" id="moths">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="detail-layout">
        <div class="detail-specimen">
          <div class="specimen-panel">
            <img src="/images/shutterstock_117988558.jpg" alt="Indian meal moth" width="1000" height="667" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="detail-text reveal">
          <span class="detail-tag">Pantry Pest</span>
          <h2>Indian Meal Moths</h2>
          <div class="pest-types">
            <div class="pest-type">
              <p>One of the most common stored product pests found in homes and food processing facilities. Adults are more active at dusk and are attracted to light.</p>
              <p>The larvae feed on coarsely ground flour and meal but commonly feed on whole grains, dried fruit, nuts, chocolate, beans, crackers, biscuits, dry dog food, bird seed, and red peppers.</p>
              <p>Larvae produce a silk webbing over the surface of materials they're feeding on, containing large amounts of frass. If you suspect a problem, discard any infested food and store all other food in sealed containers.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SILVERFISH & EARWIGS -->
  <section class="pest-detail pest-detail-alt section" id="silverfish">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="detail-layout detail-layout-reverse">
        <div class="detail-specimen">
          <div class="specimen-panel">
            <img src="/images/shutterstock_125946692.jpg" alt="Silverfish" width="1000" height="667" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
          <div class="specimen-panel specimen-panel-sm">
            <img src="/images/shutterstock_105012449.jpg" alt="Earwig" width="1000" height="667" loading="lazy" />
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="detail-text reveal">
          <span class="detail-tag">Moisture Pest</span>
          <h2>Silverfish &amp; Earwigs</h2>
          <div class="pest-types">
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Silverfish</h3>
              <p>Always wingless, silvery to brown, covered in fine scales. Adults are up to 3/4 inch long, flattened, elongated and oval with three long tail projections and two long antennae.</p>
              <p>They prefer carbohydrates and protein, including flour, dried meat, rolled oats, paper, and glue. They can survive long periods without food but require high humidity (75% to 90%) and temperatures between 70 and 80 degrees F.</p>
              <p>Primarily a nuisance pest. They can contaminate food, damage paper goods, stain clothing, and occasionally damage book bindings, curtains, and wallpaper.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="pest-type">
              <h3>Earwigs</h3>
              <p>Moisture-loving insects that typically live outdoors in damp, sheltered spots. They enter homes seeking moisture and shelter, especially during dry spells. While their pincers look alarming, they are generally harmless to people.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="services-cta section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="cta-block reveal">
        <h2>Not sure what you're dealing with?</h2>
        <p>Call and describe what you're seeing. We'll identify it and give you a price over the phone.</p>
        <a href="tel:412-854-2224" class="btn btn-primary btn-lg">Call 412-854-2224</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>

<style>
  .page-hero {
    padding-top: calc(80px + var(--space-xl));
    padding-bottom: var(--space-lg);
    background:
      linear-gradient(180deg, oklch(0.12 0.02 155 / 0.3) 0%, var(--black) 100%);
  }

  .page-title {
    font-size: clamp(3rem, 7vw, 7rem);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .page-intro {
    color: var(--text-dim);
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    max-width: 600px;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* ============ PEST DETAIL SECTIONS ============ */
  .pest-detail {
    scroll-margin-top: 80px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .pest-detail-alt {
    background: var(--dark);
  }

  .detail-layout {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 0.45fr 0.55fr;
    gap: var(--space-xl);
    align-items: start;
  }

  .detail-layout-reverse {
    grid-template-columns: 0.55fr 0.45fr;

    .detail-specimen {
      order: 1;
    }
  }

  .detail-specimen {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-sm);
    position: sticky;
    top: 100px;
  }

  .specimen-panel {
    background: var(--specimen-bg);
    border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
    padding: var(--space-md);
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    box-shadow: 0 8px 30px oklch(0 0 0 / 0.3);
    border: 1px solid oklch(0.3 0.01 145 / 0.2);
    overflow: hidden;

    img {
      width: 100%;
      height: auto;
      border-radius: var(--radius);
      transition: transform 0.8s cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1);
    }

    &:hover img {
      transform: scale(1.06);
    }
  }

  .specimen-panel-sm {
    max-width: 60%;
  }

  .detail-tag {
    display: inline-block;
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--green);
    background: var(--green-glass);
    padding: 0.3rem 0.8rem;
    border-radius: 100px;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
  }

  .detail-tag-warn {
    color: oklch(0.75 0.15 60);
    background: oklch(0.75 0.15 60 / 0.12);
  }

  .detail-text h2 {
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 5vw, 4.5rem);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
  }

  .pest-types {
    display: grid;
    gap: var(--space-md);
  }

  .pest-type {
    h3 {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      color: var(--green);
      margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
      letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    }

    p {
      color: var(--text-dim);
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      line-height: 1.7;
      margin-bottom: 0.6rem;

      &:last-child {
        margin-bottom: 0;
      }
    }
  }

  .pest-warning {
    background: oklch(0.75 0.15 60 / 0.08);
    border-left: 3px solid oklch(0.75 0.15 60);
    padding: var(--space-sm) var(--space-md);
    border-radius: 0 var(--radius) var(--radius) 0;

    strong {
      color: oklch(0.85 0.12 60);
    }
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .detail-layout,
    .detail-layout-reverse {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .detail-layout-reverse .detail-specimen {
      order: 0;
    }

    .detail-specimen {
      position: static;
      flex-direction: row;
    }

    .specimen-panel-sm {
      max-width: 40%;
    }
  }

  /* ============ SERVICES CTA ============ */
  .services-cta {
    text-align: center;
    background:
      radial-gradient(ellipse at 50% 50%, oklch(0.15 0.04 155 / 0.3), transparent 60%),
      var(--black);
  }

  .cta-block {
    h2 {
      font-family: var(--font-display);
      font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 3.5rem);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
    }

    p {
      color: var(--text-dim);
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      margin-bottom: var(--space-md);
    }
  }

  .btn {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    padding: 0.75rem 1.75rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.03em;
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    transition: all 0.25s ease;
  }

  .btn-primary {
    background: var(--green);
    color: var(--black);

    &:hover {
      background: var(--green-bright);
      box-shadow: 0 0 30px oklch(0.72 0.19 155 / 0.3);
    }
  }

  .btn-lg {
    padding: 1rem 2.5rem;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
  }
</style>
